# Task 4 \- Connor Lariviere  
In this section we are tasked with sniffing and then spoofing packets sent/received from various IP addresses. Shown below is the code used to sniff and spoof. The spoof function prints out the information of the original ICMP packet, and then spoofs a return packet by swapping the source and the destination ip addresses. It creates the packet by stacking the ip, icmp, and data into a new packet.   
![][image20]  
The filter is set to look for ICMP and packets for the current host we are trying to attack. In this attack we go through 3 different IP addresses:  
1.2.3.4   	: a non-existing host on the Internet   
10.9.0.99 	: a non-existing host on the LAN   
8.8.8.8   	: an existing host on the Internet

![][image21]  
In our first test, we go for 1.2.3.4, which is a non-existing host on the internet. We have two hosts on the same LAN. The one on the left is running the sniff and spoof program and is monitoring LAN. The one on the right is pinging each address.

With every ping we send, our program sniffs the return packet, prints the information of the original packet and creates a spoofed packet. There are 14 packets transmitted and received with no packet loss, meaning the packets were successfully sent

![][image22]  
Now, we switch the filter to our next IP address for our second test, which is a nonexistent LAN address. When we attempt the same process, our ping host reports that our destination host is unreachable.

![][image23]  
Our sniff and spoof does nothing, as there are no return packets to sniff.  
![][image24]  
The reason that we do not get any return packets is because of the way ARP functions. When sending something to a computer on the same network, or over LAN, ARP has connected the machine’s MAC address to an IP address. Because there is no MAC address related to the LAN IP address, no ICMP packet can be created.

![][image25]  
Finally, we ping 8.8.8.8 which is an existing address on the internet relating to Google. In this scenario, our ping data reports duplicates equal to the amount of packets 8.8.8.8 sends back. This is showing that our spoofing is working, as every duplicate relates to one spoofed packet.
